Please see the note below and/or share this status. \n\n***\n\nWe are writing today to invite your student organization to participate in this year's marathon on Sunday, December 8 by creating a cheer station along the marathon and half marathon routes to support and encourage runner\u2019s along the way. \n\nThis is a great opportunity for your organization for a couple of reasons! \n\nFirst, we are offering cash prizes for the top three organizations! 1st place will receive $1,500, 2nd place $1,000 and 3rd place $500. The prize money will be given as a lump sum and your organization can use it however you'd like. \n\nAnother great reason to participate is because your organization will be seen by over 4,000 runners on race day, so this is a good way to get your organization's name out in our community and show the true spirit of Aggieland as runners make their way through the campus on race day.\n\n**In order to participate, your organization needs to be able to commit to their station for 5 hours minimum with at least 10 members at the location at all times. We will assign your organization somewhere on A&M campus tocheer. The people at the station need to be willing to enthusiastically cheer on runners throughout the duration of their time at their station. You should also coordinate among group members to \"brand\" your station uniquely. You can make signs, play music, wear matching shirts, or anything else that you think would be fun and encouraging for runner\u2019s as they go by and help your group to be the most memorable! We will assign each group a color to wear and incorporate in your station so that the judges will have an easier time associating the different groups.**\n\nJudges will be running the marathon and half marathon and will use the criteria above, as well as the coordinated effort among group members, enthusiasm in cheering, creativity, and number of members present to determine the top 3 winners of the cash prizes. \n\nWe are really excited about the possibility of partnering with students at Texas A&M to make this year\u2019s race better than ever. We are only looking for 12 student organizations to participate. This is first come, first serve for the groups that can meet the above mentioned criteria. Please e-mail us with your groups name, number of members and a contact name and phone number if you would like to participate. \n\nIf you have any additional questions, feel free to e-mail us at info@bcsmarathon.com."}

They were invited to teach at many places including a large orphanage. \n\nAbout 100 boys and girls who had been abandoned, abused, and left in the care of a government- run program were in the orphanage. The two Americans relate the following story in their own words:  It was nearing the holiday season, 1994, time for our orphans to hear, for the first time, the traditional story of Christmas. \n  \n\n We told them about Mary and Joseph arriving in Bethlehem. \n\nFinding no room in the inn, the couple went to a stable, where the Baby Jesus was born and placed in a manger. Throughout the story, the children and orphanage staff sat in amazement as they listened. \n\nSome sat on the edges of their stools, trying to grasp every word.  Completing the story, we gave the children three small pieces of cardboard to make a crude manger. Each child was given a small paper square, cut from yellow napkins I had brought with me. \n\nFollowing instructions, the children tore the paper and carefully laid strips in the manger for straw.  Small squares of flannel, cut from a worn-out nightgown an American lady was throwing away as she left Russia, were used for the baby's blanket.  A doll-like baby was cut from tan felt we had brought from the United States.\n  \n\nThe orphans were busy assembling their manger as I walked among them to see if they needed any help. \n\nAll went well until I got to one table where little Misha sat.  He looked to be about 6 years old and had finished his project. \n\nAs I looked at the little boy's manger, I was startled to see not one, but two babies in the manger. Quickly, I called for the translator to ask the lad why there were two babies in the manger.\n\nCrossing his arms in front of him and looking at this completed manger scene, the child began to repeat the story very seriously. \n\nFor such a young boy, who had only heard the Christmas story once, he related the happenings accurately--until he came to the part where Mary put the Baby Jesus in the manger. \n\nThen Misha started to ad-lib. He made up his own ending to the story as he said, \"And when Maria laid the baby in the manger, Jesus looked at me and asked me if I had a place to stay.  I told him I have no mamma and I have no papa, so I don't have any place to stay.  Then Jesus told me I could stay with Him. \n  \n\nBut I told Him I could not, because I didn't have a gift to give Him like everybody else did. \n\nBut I wanted to stay with Jesus so much, so I thought about what I had that maybe I could use for a gift. I thought maybe if I kept Him warm, that would be a good gift. \n\nSo I asked Jesus, \"If I keep you warm, will that be a good enough gift?\"  And Jesus told me, \"If you keep me warm, that will be the best gift anybody ever gave me.\" \n\n\"So I got into the manger,and then Jesus looked at me and he told me I could stay with him -- for always.\" \n\nAs little Misha finished his story, his eyes brimmed full of tears that splashed down his little cheeks.  Putting his hand over his face, his head dropped to the table and his shoulders shook as he sobbed and sobbed.  The little orphan hand found someone who would never abandon nor abuse him.  Someone who would stay with him -- for always. \n\nI've learned that it's not what you have in your life, but who you have in your life that counts. \n\nAuthor unknown.", "type": "status", "id": "31302110823_10150990292220824", "comments": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MTAxNTA5OTAzMjEyMzU4MjQ=", "before": "MTAxNTA5OTAzMjEyMzU4MjQ="}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "607651138", "name": "Jonathan Snodgrass"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-08-24T18:10:01+0000", "message": "Amen! {"from": {"id": "656237908", "name": "Joshua Aguilar"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/31302110823/posts/10150925027260824", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2012-07-25T13:17:39+0000", "to": {"data": [{"name": "Texas A&M Navigators", "id": "31302110823"}]}, "likes": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "NTIyNTQxNjk0", "before": "Nzg4NDIyMjcx"}}, "data": [{"id": "788422271", "name": "Melissa Crockett"}, {"id": "609452502", "name": "Andy Garia"}, {"id": "740172946", "name": "Simon Yau"}, {"id": "1445647314", "name": "Tori Wittman"}, {"id": "589286063", "name": "Sierra Kedroske"}, {"id": "100001023351534", "name": "Rachel Kuhlmann"}, {"id": "3007013", "name": "Heather Lane"}, {"id": "100000139761571", "name": "David Blanke"}, {"id": "1356398449", "name": "Bianca Martinez"}, {"id": "100001410879539", "name": "John Wright"}, {"id": "1367301083", "name": "Rachel M. Sprunger"}, {"id": "1515840729", "name": "Amy Jean Katterjohn"}, {"id": "667151285", "name": "Kathleen Garcia"}, {"id": "1483885418", "name": "Michelle Williams"}, {"id": "1365790544", "name": "Lacy Lynn Lovell"}, {"id": "8321305", "name": "Hannah Beard"}, {"id": "522541694", "name": "Jessica Quinones"}]}, "created_time": "2012-07-23T22:46:29+0000", "message": "Howdy ya'll,\n\nTomorrow will have been one week since the loss of Gbenga. I just wanted to give you guys an update on how things are going, and how God has blessed us this past week.\n\nThere is a lot that one questions, one wonders when things like this happens. Each of us here has processed in our own way, and I've seen a lot of upheaval in people's attitudes and mindsets. As the counselors and others have said: our lives will never be the same. But I believe I can say that, as a whole, the members and leaders and staff here at STP have drawn closer to the Lord and we are have grown deeper in the Lord and have had hour hearts knit closer together as a group through it. \n\nAnd we know that all things work together for good to those who love God, to those who are the called according to His purpose (Romans 8:28). Here are some examples of that:\n\n-One UT Nav and STP member had for so long had held intellectual barriers to God. But Gbenga was his friend, and he was one of the divers that tried to find and save him. But he couldn't do it forever, and once he got too tired to swim he had to climb up to the shore. He says that was the most humbling walk of his life, and he let go of his pride and trusted the Lord at long last that afternoon. He told Micah that there was probably no other event that would have brought him to Christ. One girl said later how Gbenga got to be part of two parties: the one welcoming him to Heaven, and the one welcoming Benny to Christ.\n\n-David and Laura Panto's three-year old son, Aaron, after talking to his parents about what happened, prayed to believe Christ. Gbenga loved the Panto boys, and I can't think of anything else that would bring him joy to know.\n\n-Prior to the Lord calling Gbenga home, one of the challenges of having a group of 47 members is that it's hard to have a tight-knit bond. After the trauma of what happened, everyone greets each other with a hug, and we encourage and comfort one another as often as we see each other. There is truly a deeper bond and warmth that none of us expected to exist at the start of the program. \n\n-The night before we went to the lake, we went over 1 Thessalonians 4:15 to 5:11, which talked about the rapture and the coming comfort of seeing those we have fallen asleep in the Lord. To have that fresh on our minds had a truly miraculous effect as we witnessed and mourned directly afterwards. We didn't grieve as those who have no hope, because we know we will be reunited with Gbenga  again one day in the clouds (1 Thess 4:13-14).\n\n-Gbenga's family has been very gracious and centered on the Lord in this time. When they could be angry or distraught, they have shown the peace of being rooted and strong in our God and Father. \n\nThere are many other things God has done in really turning the soil in each of our lives, but just to know that God has been Himself: faithful, loving, and true, and has graciously manifested that in the midst of us during this sad but hopeful time.\n\nAs we continue in the last two weeks of the program, here are some things we'd be grateful you could pray for:\n\n-Gbenga's family and friends, that as they continue to mourn his loss they would draw near to the Lord.\n\n-His team, consisting of Micah Stringer, JT Walford, and JR Alvarenga, as they continue to heal from the deep loss of their brother.\n\n-The team members and leaders as we continue to heal, deal with waves of grief as they come, and adjust to \"the new normal\".\n\n-The staff as they also adjust and guide the program in the remaining three weeks.\n\nThat these verses would continue to seek in deep, 1 Thess 5:9-11 and 16-18\n\n\"For God did not appoint us to wrath, but to obtain salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ, who died for us, that whether we wake or sleep, we should live together with Him. Btw I was looking at Hosea 10 (because I dont say exactly in my qt lol)\n\n\"The first verse says that \"Israel is a luxuriant vine\", or a degenerate vine. It's interesting that the translators of the bible said that luxuriant and degenerate are synonmous. It's like the more material things you have, the more you desire them and seek after them; that is degrading to your spiritual health. It's not saying if you are wealthy then you are less spiritual, but this is what Israel did with their wealth. Israel produced fruit for itself. The more fruit he had, the more alters he made; and the richer his land, the better he made the pillars. Isreal was investing in their alters. They believed that the more alters they had and the better they looked, they would also have a great crop. They did not rely on God to provide for them, they became faithless and turned to other things to put their faith in. Because of their reliance on the alters and pillars, God will tear them down.\nI believe we do this all the time with school and our studies. We are faithless toward God with our grades; maybe not with our words, but definately in our deeds. We say in out hearts, 'God is not great enough or mighty enough to help me in this class. Therefore, I need to study more for this subject.' If we see good fruit as a result of our hard efforts, we say, 'This is a good thing, what I am doing. So if I put more investment in this, I will get an even greater return.' However, if we don't see good fruits from our labor, we still don't return to putting our hope in God, but we find new ways to get our desired results. this isn't saying hard work is a sin or not necessary. We still have to plow a field, sow seeds, and reap the fruit, that is hard work. but where is your heart? where am I investing my faith to get the results I want?\"\n\nAs we go into finals, its so easy to pray empty prayers like, \"Lord, help me remember all the things I know\" or \"Lord, bring to my memory all the things I studied\". What does that even mean?? Instead, let us pray for our unbelief; our unbelief that God does not have the most perfect plan for our lives. I do pray you do well on your fianals and work hard and dilligently, but dont let us forget who all the glory should go to. Continue to be dilligent in your quiet times and don't let the pressures of this world hinder you from meeting with your Creator daily.\n\nWith love,\nKatelyn", "type": "status", "id": "31302110823_10150398836300824"}
